cally divides criminalized populations into gang-associated affiliations. These affiliations come to shape one’s exposure to both violence and criminal labeling, and as they spill over the institutional walls they establish how these unfold in high-incarceration neighborhoods as well, revealing the insidious set of consequences that mass incarceration holds for poor communities of color.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mai 2023) 0aPrison administrationzCalifornia. 0aPrison gangszCalifornia. 0aPrisonersxViolence againstzCalifornia. 0aPrisonerszCaliforniaxSocial conditions. 0aRace discriminationzCalifornia. 0aSocial controlzCalifornia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Criminology.2bisacsh  acarceral social order.  acriminal labeling.  acriminal rehabilitation.  aimpact of mass incarceration on communities.  ainstitutional behavior.  ajuvenile justice.  alife after prison.  amass incarceration.  apenal violence.  aprison administration.  aprison life.  arace and prisons.  aracial division in prisons.  aracism in prisons.  asocial impact of incarceration.  asurviving prison.  atransitioning back home after prison.  aviolence against prisoners.  aviolence in prison.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018z97831106676770 cprintz978052028858440uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780520963450?locatt=mode:legacy40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520963450423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780520963450/original  a978-3-11-066767-7  University of California Press Complete eBook-Package 2018b2018  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY